export const notes = "\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>1. Distribution and Growth Conditions</h3>\n  <p>Tropical rainforests are found between <strong>20\u00b0N and 20\u00b0S</strong> of the equator (the tropical zone).</p>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Key regions:</strong> Amazon Basin (Brazil), Congo Basin (DRC), Southeast Asia (Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore)\n  </div>\n  <h4>Growth Conditions</h4>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Temperature</strong>\n      <p>26\u201328\u00b0C year-round \u2014 no cold season to slow growth</p>\n      <strong>Rainfall</strong>\n      <p>&gt;2,000 mm per year, well-distributed throughout the year</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Sunlight</strong>\n      <p>Intense solar radiation year-round due to equatorial position</p>\n      <strong>Soils</strong>\n      <p>Often laterite (red, nutrient-poor topsoil) \u2014 nutrients are stored in the biomass, not the soil</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    Tropical rainforests cover only about <strong>6% of Earth's land surface</strong> but contain <strong>50\u201375% of all species</strong> on Earth.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>2. Singapore's Tropical Climate</h3>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore's Location:</strong> 1\u00b021'N \u2014 extremely close to the equator\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Temperature</strong>\n      <p>Mean annual ~27.5\u00b0C; daily range 23\u201331\u00b0C</p>\n      <strong>Rainfall</strong>\n      <p>~2,340 mm per year</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Humidity</strong>\n      <p>~84% relative humidity</p>\n      <strong>Seasons</strong>\n      <p>No distinct seasons; two monsoon periods (NE Monsoon: Dec\u2013Mar; SW Monsoon: Jun\u2013Sep) and two inter-monsoon periods</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"case-study\">\n    <strong>Singapore's Rainforest Coverage:</strong> In 1819, rainforest covered almost the entire island. Today, Singapore retains only about <strong>3% of its original rainforest</strong>. <strong>Bukit Timah Nature Reserve (163 ha)</strong> is the primary intact rainforest patch remaining.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> When asked about Singapore's climate, link its equatorial position (1\u00b021'N) to high temperatures, high rainfall, and high humidity year-round.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>3. The Four Layers of the Tropical Rainforest</h3>\n  <p>The tropical rainforest has a distinct layered structure. Each layer has different light levels, height, and species.</p>\n  <table style=\"width:100%;border-collapse:collapse;margin-top:0.5rem;\">\n    <thead>\n      <tr style=\"background:#2d6a4f;color:#fff;\">\n        <th style=\"padding:6px 8px;text-align:left;\">Layer</th>\n        <th style=\"padding:6px 8px;text-align:left;\">Height</th>\n        <th style=\"padding:6px 8px;text-align:left;\">Key Features</th>\n        <th style=\"padding:6px 8px;text-align:left;\">Light</th>\n        <th style=\"padding:6px 8px;text-align:left;\">Examples</th>\n      </tr>\n    </thead>\n    <tbody>\n      <tr style=\"background:#f0faf5;\">\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;font-weight:bold;\">Emergent</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">40\u201360 m</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Tallest trees, isolated umbrella-shaped crowns, exposed to wind and full sun</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Full sun</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Tualang, Meranti</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;font-weight:bold;\">Canopy</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">25\u201335 m</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Dense continuous layer; most biodiversity; absorbs ~80% of incoming light</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Filtered sun</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Dipterocarp, figs</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr style=\"background:#f0faf5;\">\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;font-weight:bold;\">Understory</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">5\u201320 m</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Shrubs and small trees adapted to low light; broad leaves to capture available light</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Dim (2\u20135%)</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Palms, young trees</td>\n      </tr>\n      <tr>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;font-weight:bold;\">Forest Floor</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">0\u20135 m</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Very dark; rapid decomposition of leaf litter; roots absorb nutrients quickly</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Near dark (&lt;1%)</td>\n        <td style=\"padding:6px 8px;\">Ferns, fungi, seedlings</td>\n      </tr>\n    </tbody>\n  </table>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Learn the exact height ranges and light percentages for each layer \u2014 these are commonly tested in structured questions.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>4. Plant Adaptations</h3>\n  <p>Plants in the tropical rainforest have evolved remarkable adaptations to survive in their specific layer.</p>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>1. Buttress Roots</strong> \u2014 Large triangular root flanges extend from the base of emergent trees. They spread the weight of the tall tree across a wider area, providing support in shallow, nutrient-poor soil.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>2. Drip Tips</strong> \u2014 Pointed leaf tips allow rainwater to drip off quickly, preventing the growth of algae and fungi on the leaf surface, which would block sunlight and damage the leaf.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>3. Waxy / Thick Cuticle</strong> \u2014 A shiny, waterproof leaf surface repels excess water and reduces damage from heavy tropical rainfall.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>4. Large Leaves</strong> \u2014 Leaves can be up to 1 m wide in the understory, maximising the capture of the limited light that filters through the canopy.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>5. Lianas (Woody Vines)</strong> \u2014 These woody climbing plants grow up tree trunks using them as support, allowing them to reach sunlight without investing energy in building their own thick trunk.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>6. Epiphytes</strong> \u2014 Plants (e.g., orchids, ferns, mosses) that grow on other plants without being parasitic. They use the host plant's height to access sunlight.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>7. Stilt / Prop Roots</strong> \u2014 Aerial roots that grow from the trunk or branches down to the ground, providing extra stability in waterlogged or shallow soils.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>8. Thin Smooth Bark</strong> \u2014 There is no need for thick bark in a frost-free climate. Thin bark allows water to run off and enables faster growth.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>9. Cauliflory</strong> \u2014 Flowers and fruits grow directly on the trunk or main branches (e.g., durian, jackfruit), making them accessible to ground-dwelling and trunk-climbing pollinators and seed dispersers.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>10. Bright Coloured Fruits</strong> \u2014 Attract animals (birds, mammals) which eat the fruit and disperse the seeds away from the parent plant.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>11. Rapid Growth (Gap Dynamics)</strong> \u2014 When a large tree falls and opens a gap in the canopy, seedlings on the forest floor grow extremely quickly to exploit the sudden availability of sunlight.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Always state the adaptation AND explain HOW it helps the plant survive. \"Drip tips allow rainwater to run off quickly, preventing algae/fungi growth on the leaf, which would block sunlight.\"\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>5. Animal Adaptations</h3>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Arboreal Adaptations:</strong> Prehensile tails (monkeys), opposable thumbs, and gripping feet allow animals to live and move through the canopy without descending to the ground.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Camouflage:</strong> Stick insects, leaf insects, and green tree frogs blend with surrounding vegetation, making them nearly invisible to predators.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Nocturnal Behaviour:</strong> Many animals are active at night to avoid competition with daytime species and to take advantage of cooler nighttime temperatures.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Flying / Gliding:</strong> Flying squirrels, flying lizards, and tree frogs with webbed feet can glide between trees, allowing movement through the canopy without touching the ground.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Loud Calls:</strong> Monkeys and birds produce loud calls to communicate over long distances in dense forest where visibility is poor.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Feeding Specialisation:</strong> Toucans (large curved beak for reaching fruits), hummingbirds (long beak for nectar), anteaters (long sticky snout for extracting insects) \u2014 each species evolved to exploit a specific food source.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Singapore's Endangered Species:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li><strong>Raffles' Banded Langur</strong> \u2014 critically endangered primate found only in southern Johor and Singapore</li>\n      <li><strong>Sunda Pangolin</strong> \u2014 nocturnal, heavily poached for scales and meat</li>\n      <li><strong>Straw-headed Bulbul</strong> \u2014 critically endangered songbird, one of the world's rarest</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>6. The Nutrient Cycle</h3>\n  <p>The tropical rainforest nutrient cycle is <strong>fast and tightly closed</strong> \u2014 nutrients move rapidly between stores.</p>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Biomass Store: LARGE</strong>\n      <p>Most nutrients are locked in living vegetation (trees, roots, leaves). The system holds vast amounts of carbon and nitrogen in plant tissue.</p>\n      <strong>Litter Store: SMALL</strong>\n      <p>Leaf litter decomposes in as little as <strong>6 weeks</strong> in a tropical rainforest (vs. years in a temperate forest) due to heat, moisture, and intense decomposer activity.</p>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Soil Store: SMALL and SHALLOW</strong>\n      <p>Laterite soils are nutrient-poor. Almost all available nutrients are in the top few centimetres of soil.</p>\n      <strong>Leaching Risk: HIGH</strong>\n      <p>Heavy rainfall washes soluble nutrients down through the soil profile. Plants must absorb nutrients rapidly before they are lost.</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Mycorrhizal Fungi:</strong> Symbiotic fungi attached to plant roots that break down organic matter and pass nutrients <em>directly</em> to the roots \u2014 a critical mechanism for rapid nutrient uptake.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    <strong>Fragility Warning:</strong> If vegetation is removed through deforestation, nutrients are rapidly lost through leaching. The poor laterite soil cannot support crops for long. The system collapses and recovery is very slow.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> Describe the nutrient cycle using the three stores (biomass, litter, soil) and the key processes (decomposition, uptake, leaching). Explain WHY the system is fragile \u2014 nutrients are in the biomass, not the soil.\n  </div>\n</div>\n\n<div class=\"notes-card\">\n  <h3>7. Biodiversity</h3>\n  <div class=\"stat-callout\">\n    ~6% of Earth's land surface \u2192 contains <strong>50\u201375% of ALL plant and animal species</strong> on Earth\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"compare-grid\">\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Amazon Rainforest</strong>\n      <ul>\n        <li>~40,000 plant species</li>\n        <li>~1,300 bird species</li>\n        <li>~3,000 freshwater fish species</li>\n      </ul>\n    </div>\n    <div class=\"compare-col\">\n      <strong>Medicines</strong>\n      <p>~50% of all medicines worldwide are derived from or inspired by rainforest plants.</p>\n      <strong>Southeast Asia (Sundaland)</strong>\n      <p>One of the world's 36 biodiversity hotspots</p>\n    </div>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"sg-spotlight\">\n    <strong>Bukit Timah Nature Reserve (BTNR), Singapore \u2014 163 ha:</strong>\n    <ul>\n      <li>Home to <strong>1,250 plant species</strong></li>\n      <li>Contains more species of trees than the entire continent of North America</li>\n      <li>One of the highest biodiversity per unit area sites on Earth</li>\n    </ul>\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"example\">\n    <strong>Threats to Biodiversity:</strong> Habitat loss (deforestation for agriculture, logging, urban development), climate change, forest fragmentation, and illegal hunting/poaching.\n  </div>\n  <div class=\"exam-tip\">\n    <strong>Exam Tip:</strong> When asked to \"describe\" or \"explain\" adaptations \u2014 always state the adaptation, then explain HOW it helps survival. E.g., \"Drip tips allow water to run off quickly, preventing the growth of algae and fungi on the leaf surface, which would block sunlight and damage the leaf.\"\n  </div>\n</div>\n";

